The TCP/IP model (also called the Internet Protocol Suite) is the real-world framework that governs how data is transmitted on the Internet. Itâ€™s simpler and more practical than OSI.

ğŸ”¹ Layers of TCP/IP

> Network Access (Link) Layer

Combines OSIâ€™s physical + data link functions.

Responsible for hardware transmission (Ethernet, Wi-Fi).

> Internet Layer

Handles logical addressing, packet formation, and routing using IP.

Protocols include IP, ICMP, ARP.

> Transport Layer

Ensures data delivery services between hosts.

Uses TCP for reliable connections and UDP for fast, connectionless communication.

> Application Layer

Closest to users and applications.

Combines OSIâ€™s Application, Presentation, and Session functions.

Protocols: HTTP, FTP, DNS, SMTP, etc.

* Why it matters: The Internet runs on TCP/IP. Understanding this stack helps you grasp real network traffic and how protocols operate endâ€toâ€end.

ğŸ§®  IP Addressing â€” Identifying Devices

An IP address is a unique identifier for a device on a network, similar to a postal address for mail delivery. It allows routers and other devices to locate and communicate with each other across networks.

ğŸ”¹ Version Differences

IPv4 â€” 32-bit address (like 192.168.1.1).

IPv6 â€” 128-bit address (like 2001:db8::1), created because IPv4 addresses were running out.

